There are multiple such methods in Java.

### [`String.format(String, Object...)`](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#format%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.Object...%29)
&gt; Returns a formatted string using the specified format string and arguments. 

and

### [`System.out`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/System.html#out) can use [`PrintStream.printf(String, Object...)`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/io/PrintStream.html#printf%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.Object...%29)

and

### The [`Formatter` syntax](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Formatter.html#syntax) applies to both of the above

For example,

	String fmt = &quot;i = %d%n&quot;;
	int iv = 101;
	System.out.print(String.format(fmt, iv));
	System.out.printf(fmt, iv);
	Formatter out = new Formatter(System.out);
	out.format(fmt, iv);
	out.flush();

